  "response": "People often have several common frustrations with physics:\n\n1. Mathematical complexity\n- Advanced math requirements\n- Complex equations and formulas\n- Abstract mathematical concepts\n\n2. Counterintuitive concepts\n- Quantum mechanics challenges common sense\n- Relativity defies everyday experience\n- Particle-wave duality seems impossible\n\n3. Theoretical nature\n- Many theories can't be directly observed\n- Some concepts seem disconnected from practical reality\n- Difficulty understanding highly abstract ideas\n\n4. Learning challenges\n- Steep learning curve\n- Requires strong analytical skills\n- Involves significant problem-solving\n\n5. Computational difficulty\n- Complex calculations\n- Requires precise thinking\n- Demands high levels of concentration\n\n6. Philosophical implications\n- Quantum uncertainty\n- Questions about consciousness and reality\n- Challenges to deterministic worldviews\n\n7. Advanced instrumentation\n- Expensive research equipment\n- Limited experimental capabilities\n- Reliance on complex technology\n\n8. Philosophical and practical limitations\n- Some phenomena can only be probabilistically described\n- Limits of human perception and understanding\n- Gaps in current scientific knowledge\n\nThese frustrations vary by individual but represent common themes in people's experiences with physics.",
